                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d156">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14969</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Far Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi>)<note n="12" xml:id="d156fn12"
                        >Commenting on memorandum by John S. Service dated January 23, <ref
                            target="#pg_193">p. 193</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-28">January 28,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Kuomintang-Communist situation in China is one which we should, of course,
                    follow with care. A few days ago we asked Mr. Gauss by telegram to send us a
                    report on the matter. Upon the receipt of his report, it is suggested that we
                    give careful consideration to the question of asking the Embassy to send an
                    officer to visit the Communist areas.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>M[<hi rend="smallcaps">axwell</hi>] M. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >amilton</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
